                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, frankly I think this is just a failed relationship, and you broke up as many couples do once they find out they're incompatible. It definitely hurts, and it definitely sucks and it's definitely going to be ok. I'll share some of my personal exeriences with you since I dated a few people from EQ and am now happily engaged and having a great time. It's not all tears and screw ups. 
<br />

<br />
Firstly, it's really easy to get caught up with someone before you've met with them face to face. The way I see it for every year you've known someone online you've really only known them for a month's worth of face to face interaction. When you consider that this thread will probably get responses for a couple days, and face to face the conversation could have taken place in the span of  about 2 minute tops you begin to see why 'time' is somewhat skewed on the net. 
<br />

<br />
That being said, we are used to saying 'well I've known them for a year, I'm in a good position to evaluate who this person is' and unless you actively slow yourself down online chances are you're going to get hurt. I really feel it was this false expectation that created this painful situtation for you, and it's a very natural pitfall for first time internet daters to run into - I certainly did serveral times before figuring this hard lesson out.
<br />

<br />
So where do you go from here? Well - he's different face to face the online - no shocker there since you're getting to know what he's really like for the first time. Aristotle used to promote the idea that you define the charecter of a man by his actions - not his words. I think that's very sound advice especially in a relationship and something you definitely need to meet them in person to discover before you can tell if they're 'the one' for you. So you've met him and we know a bit more about how you felt after that.
<br />

<br />
Firstly you had a nagging saying 'he's different' - why was that voice there? What warning flags went up? How exactly was he different from your expectations? What exactly ARE your expectations in a relationship and is he satisfying them? How does he make you feel? A wise friend of mine once said 'if you don't know exactly what you want then how are you going to know when you have it?' and I think that leads to some quality introspection. 
<br />

<br />
You also mentioned that he was more distant from you then you from him - I think this is a very serious problem. He enjoys his space and his distance, and you enjoy closeness and chances are this will never change. Relationships with this sort of disparity are hurtful to both parties, since you'll be upset that he's pulling away and you'll be upset that you're trying to be close. I'm a 'clingy' person in that I want to spend all my time with the person I'm in love with. 24/7 of that person are what I really enjoy, and I knew that when I found the right person they'd be the same and want to spend 24/7 with me. For those who enjoy more distance they do alot better with someone who also enjoys more distance because they'll both want to be apart from each other at times. You'll need to ask yourself what you really envision your future to be like, and what you are expecting from that person. 
<br />

<br />
That being said, I don't think you 'screwed up' so much as you got angry when you really shouldn't have. It's not his fault that you're incompatible, it's simply the way it is. I think the screw up was more that you let yourself become over emotionally involved before you had enough information to make a good decision. Long distance relationships are harder then most, and unless it's really a very compatible match right from the get go it's probably not worth the extra effort. 
<br />

<br />
As a final note - if you don't want to feel like you're being used for sex then don't have sex with them early in the relationship! Everyone has different standards and expectations in a relationship and accusing him of using you for a **** is definitely out of line. You fully participated and had the ability to not do so if you didn't feel you were ready to for whatever reason. If sex is something you only want to do with those who are commited to you in a deep and serious manner you should not be having sex with someone until you know without a doubt that he felt that way about you. 
<br />

<br />
If you consider sex a more recreational activity then it's certainly unfair to use it as a guilt card because you were unhappy. I think you had many good reasons to be upset and frustrated and confused, none the less you did blow it out of proportion. This again is likely due to the confusion the internet causes and the false sense of knowing someone before you meet them face to face. I really hope you don't write of internet dating because of one bad incident much like I would hope you don't write off traditional dating practices because of bad experiences as well. I'm certainly hoping you find someone great who makes you feel well and is very much the man you're hoping to be with. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />1010011010 - Binary of the Beast!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
