                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=53124#53124"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Jun 29, 2004 11:08 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=53124"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">When I said he 'felt different' I don't mean he felt different to how he was online, he was pretty much how I'd expected. I mean he didn't feel quite the same way about me as I felt about him.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
Right now I'm just doing the waiting thing while he thinks things over, and that in itself is hard for me, although its giving me some good headspace to think about it all myself. When you have these bolt of lightning connections with people, the kind that happen only a few times in a lifetime, they dont always lead to a good relationship but they do always lead to having to think about some seriously heavy stuff.  <img src="images/smiles/eusa_eh.gif" alt="eusa_eh.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
On a side note - has anyone else thought about how amazing it is the way we can pick people out online based on such small signals? I was drawn to this guy when I hardly knew him, nor did anyone else - he was renouned as one of the most standoffish folks about, (not the type I usually connect with in EQ) - so all I had to go on was the little details of how he was in /gu and /gsay. And yet when we got to know each other out of game, it turned out the similarities in our family backgrounds were spooky. There's a psychology paper in here for someone to write I guess. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
